Introduction¶

Research Question¶

How many days into the future is it possible to reliably forecast the hospital chain's revenue using time series modeling techniques?

Objectives & Goals¶

Goal 1: Develop a reliable [Seasonal] Autoregressive Integrated Moving Average ([S]ARIMA) model using the hospital chain's daily revenue

  • Objective 1: Determine whether the data contains any seasonality
  • Objective 2: Determine whether the data contains any trends
  • Objective 3: Determine whether the any autocorrelation exists within the dataset
  • Objective 4: Train the [S]ARIMA model accounting for objectives 1-3

Goal 2: Determine the longest possible accurate forecast period for the model selected in Goal 1

  • Objective 1: Create a 30-day forecast using the model from Goal 1
  • Objective 2: Measure the accuracy of the forecasted values for each day
  • Objective 3: Identify where the accuracy of the forecast drops below acceptable levels

Initial Data State¶

The original dataset was formated with Day and Revenue columns, both numeric. To prepare the dataset for time series analysis a datetime index was created from the Day column resulting in a final index ranging from 1/1/2020 through 12/31/2021.

Model Selection¶

Several steps were taken to select the best [S]ARIMA model for the dataset.

Stationarity¶

The I in SARIMA stands for Integrated and determines the number of differences needed to make the time series stationary. The Augmented Dickey Fuller (ADF) test was used to test the null hypothesis that the data is not stationary. A p-value less than .05 means the null hypothesis can be rejected. In this case it can't, meaning the data is not stationary.

In [ ]:
from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import adfuller

adf = adfuller(df, autolag='AIC')
adf_df = pd.Series(adf[:4], index=['Test Statistic', 'p-value', 'Lags', 'Observations'])
for k, v in adf[4].items():
    adf_df[f'Critical Value {k}'] = v
print('Augmented Dickey Fuller test:')
adf_df

To coerce stationarity, the first difference was taken and the ADF test was reran. This time, the p-value is well below .05 meaning the null-hypothesis can be rejected and the data can be considered stationary.

df_train = df.loc[:'2021-11-30']
df_test = df.loc['2021-12-01':]

Seasonality¶

Seasonality was assessed in a couple of different ways. First, the autocorrelation function was plotted over the detrended data. Detrending was performed by subtracting the rolling 180-day mean from each value. 180 days was selected because it is typical for hospital revenue to cycle at 90 days. Using double the expected season allows differences across potential seasons to be minimized. If any seasonality existed, there would be periodic spikes in the plot. Since there are not, the data is non-seasonal.

In [ ]:
from statsmodels.graphics.tsaplots import plot_acf
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

detrend = df_train - df_train.rolling(180).mean()
detrend.dropna(inplace=True)

_, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 3))
plot_acf(detrend, lags=180, zero=False, title='Detrended Daily Revenue', ax=ax)
ax.set_xlabel('Lags')
ax.set_ylabel('Correlation')
plt.tight_layout()
print()








    
    



































The auto_arima function was also used to confirm the lack of seasonality in the dataset. This function iteratively tests the hyperparameters to find the best model fit, including seasonal models, if applicable. The final model identified was ARIMA(1,1,0) with no seasonal components.

Autocorrelation¶
In the previous section, the order of the ARIMA model identified was (1,1,0). This indicates that an AR(1) model should be used after taking the first difference of the time series. To confirm these findings, the autocorrelation and partial autocorrelation functions were plotted. In the partial autocorrelation plot, only the first lag is correlated. This implies that the reason for any correlation in the second lag of the autocorrelation plot is only a result of it including correlation from the first lag. This confirms the auto_arima findings that an AR(1) model is best suited to the time series.



















In [ ]:



     


from statsmodels.graphics.tsaplots import plot_pacf

df_train_diff = df_train.diff().dropna()
_, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(2, figsize=(10, 6))

ax1.set_xlabel('Lags')
ax1.set_ylabel('Correlation')

Model Evaluation¶
The model was evaluated using the Mean Absolute Error (MAE) and the plot_diagnostics method of the model. The formula for MAE is:

$$MAE = {1 \over n}{\sum_{i=1}^{n}|x_i-x|}$$
The MAE for the predictions made on the training data was $0.35 million. Reviewing the diagnostic plots, it can be seen that the residuals are normally distributed and are not autocorrelated.



















In [ ]:



     


mae = np.mean(np.abs(res.resid))
print('Mean Absolute Error:', mae, '\n')
res.plot_diagnostics(figsize=(9, 6))
plt.tight_layout()

Forecast¶
The 30-day forecast was generated for comparison with the testing data.



















In [ ]:



     


forecast = res.get_forecast(30)
ci = forecast.conf_int()
predicted_mean = forecast.predicted_mean

_, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 3))
df.plot(ax=ax, color='b')
predicted_mean.plot(ax=ax, color='r', label='Forecasted Revenue')
ax.fill_between(ci.index, ci['lower Revenue'], ci['upper Revenue'],
                 color='r', alpha=0.2, label='95% Confidence Interval')
ax.set_title('Observed Revenue with 30-day Forecast')
plt.legend()
plt.tight_layout()



     




















    
    



































Measure¶
To evaluate the forecast quality at 1- to 30-day intervals, the cumualtive MAE was calculated. For interpretability, the proportion MAE of Revenue at the end of each period was also calculated.



















In [ ]:



     


metric_df = df_test.join(forecast.predicted_mean)
metric_df['resid'] = metric_df.predicted_mean.sub(metric_df.Revenue)
metric_df['cum_mae'] = metric_df.resid.abs().cumsum().div(metric_df.index.day)
metric_df['cum_mae_pct_Revenue'] = metric_df.cum_mae.div(metric_df.Revenue)

fig, (ax1, ax2, ax3) = plt.subplots(3, sharex=True, figsize=(10, 10))
fig.suptitle('30-day Forecast Metrics')
metric_df.resid.plot(ax=ax1, grid=True, marker='o', title='Error')
metric_df.cum_mae.plot(ax=ax2, grid=True, marker='o',
                       title='Cumulative Mean Absolute Error')
metric_df.cum_mae_pct_Revenue.plot(ax=ax3, grid=True, marker='o',
                                   title='Percent Cumulative Mean '
                                         'Absolute Error of Revenue')
plt.tight_layout()

Identify¶
From the information above, a few conclusions can be drawn. First, the predicted mean of the forecasted values flatlines beginning on December 15th, 2021, or at two weeks. This behavior is expected because of the nature of a time series model that only accounts for a single lag. These models must use predicted values to predict further than one step into the future. This means the predictions become less valuable the farther into the future they are. For this reason, the model should not be used to forecast farther than two weeks into the future.


The second finding was that the highest cumulative MAE occurred at 10 days with a value of ${+\over}$$2.05 million or 10.38% of the revenue at 10 days. This further shortens the length of the reliable forecast length to under 10 days.


Depending on the operating margins of the hospital chain, a more conservative forecast period should be used. In the 1- and 2-day forecasts, the margin of error is below 5%. To be safe, no longer than a 7-day period should be forecasted using the model with the currently collected data.

Recommendations¶
The model should be used in an exploratory fashion to continue model evaluation for 7-day forecasts. Though, without model updates, it is likely that the model will not maintain any level of accuracy for long in the beginning. This leads to the second recommendation, which is to collect more data with which the model can be updated. This is needed for two reasons. First, time series models are more accurate when supplied with recent data. Second, the first year of data is reflective of the organizations state as a startup. The trends appear to normalize in the second year. With continued evaluation, seasons may become visible, allowing the model to forecast more accurately, and farther into the future. The last recommendation is to automate the process of staging the most recent data and updating the model. By automating this step, the model will always have access to the most recent data, allowing data science efforts to focus on tuning the model for the best performance rather than obtaining more training data.
